Analysis of Beta4.1 — Functional Requirements Review
I've analyzed the codebase against your 11 requirements. Here are my findings — broken down per requirement, with bugs/issues highlighted.

✅ 1. Source server holds the program; bootstrapper SFTPs to check version
Working. bootstrapper.py::_sync() opens SFTP, reads /opt/cloud_health/version.txt, compares with the local cached version, and pulls the tree only on mismatch.
⚠️ Bug — Path mismatch between bootstrapper and frontend:

Bootstrapper: REMOTE_ROOT = "/opt/cloud_health"
frontend/core/version_sync.py: REMOTE_ROOT = "/opt/cloudhealth" (no underscore)

These two modules disagree on where the source program lives. If anyone uses the frontend's version_sync.py, it will look in the wrong directory.
[FIXED] version_sync.py updated to REMOTE_ROOT = "/opt/cloud_health"

⚠️ Bug — Cache directory mismatch:

Bootstrapper uses ~/.cloud_health/
frontend/core/credentials.py uses ~/.cloudhealth/

They are separate cred stores and never share data.
[FIXED] credentials.py and config.py updated to use ~/.cloud_health/


❌ 2. Bootstrapper asks for credentials, saves encrypted, retries on failure
Partially working — retry on failed login is MISSING.
The bootstrapper:

Shows a browser popup ✅
Encrypts credentials with Fernet+PBKDF2 ✅
Saves only when "remember" is ticked ✅

But: if _sync() fails (wrong password, bad host, bad port), the code does:
python except Exception as e:
    print(f"[bootstrap] ERROR: {e}")
    sys.exit(1)
It exits immediately. There is no loop that re-prompts the user. The requirement says "if login failed, ask the user to enter credentials again" — that retry logic is not implemented.
[FIXED] Retry loop implemented (3 attempts); error shown in browser UI on each failed attempt.

⚠️ Additional bug — cached credentials are never used: load_creds() is defined but never called in main(). The popup is shown every single time, even when valid credentials exist in cache. The "remember credentials" checkbox is effectively useless.
[FIXED] load_creds() called at startup; popup skipped if cached credentials succeed.

⚠️ Security bug: save_creds() is called before the connection is tested. If the user types a wrong password, it gets encrypted and saved to disk anyway.
[FIXED] save_creds() moved to after successful _sync() validation.


✅ 3. Connection failure → error message and exit
Working (though see point 2 — it should retry, not just exit). The exception is caught and sys.exit(1) is called with a printed error. The frontend popup, however, does not display the error visually since the browser tab has already been closed by server.shutdown().
⚠️ UX bug: The error only goes to stdout/stderr. If the bootstrapper is run as a PyInstaller .exe with no console, the user never sees the error.
[FIXED] Error message surfaced in browser UI via /status polling endpoint; visible even with no console.


⚠️ 4. Bootstrapper SFTPs backend+frontend with dependencies, launches, goes to background until healthcheck completes
Partially working.

SFTP pull recursively copies the program tree ✅ (via _sftp_pull)
Launches main.py via subprocess.Popen ✅

Issues:
⚠️ Dependencies are NOT bundled. _sftp_pull only copies /opt/cloud_health/*. There is no logic to install Python dependencies (paramiko, fastapi, uvicorn, cryptography, pandas, openpyxl, websockets, pyyaml). The bootstrapper assumes they exist on the user's machine. The requirement says "with all their dependencies" — this is not fulfilled.
[FIXED] vendor/ and requirements.txt pushed via SFTP; offline pip install (--no-index --find-links vendor/) runs before backend launch. vendor/ is mandatory — RuntimeError raised if missing.

⚠️ Bootstrapper exits immediately after Popen: Look at the end of main():
python subprocess.Popen([sys.executable, str(main_py)], cwd=str(PROGRAM_DIR))
There's no wait(), no monitoring of the child, no "stay alive until healthcheck completes." The bootstrapper exits as soon as it spawns the process. The requirement says it should "go to background until healthcheck complete" — this is not implemented.
[IGNORED] Accepted as-is; bootstrapper spawning frontend and exiting is the intended behaviour.

⚠️ No backend launch at all from bootstrapper: The bootstrapper only launches main.py (the frontend). The backend on the cluster bastions is launched later by the frontend, not the bootstrapper.
[IGNORED] Design is intentional — frontend manages bastion backend lifecycle.


✅ 5. Frontend welcome page: select checks, change config, start healthcheck
Working. frontend/static/index.html has:

A "Test Cases" tab with check-group selection
A "Configuration" tab with parallel limit, max parallel nodes, SSH timeout, command timeout, all thresholds (disk %, mem warn/fail %, swap, load), output dir, inventory file
A "Run Health Check" button that posts start_all over /ws/ui

/api/config GET/POST persists changes back to config.yaml.


⚠️ 6. Check inventory & credentials, SFTP backend to all clusters (/tmp/health_check/ if version differs), start backend
Mostly working — with a path mismatch.
The flow in frontend/app.py::_run_single_cluster() correctly:

Loads inventory ✅
Opens SSH+tunnel to each cluster bastion ✅
Calls sftp_push_backend() which compares versions and pushes only on mismatch ✅
Launches backend via nohup python3 ... main.py --port {N} ✅

⚠️ Bug — Path mismatch with your spec: You specified /tmp/health_check/, but the code uses /tmp/cloud_health/ (REMOTE_BACKEND_DIR = "/tmp/cloud_health" in tunnel_manager.py). Functionally consistent within the code, but does not match your stated requirement.
[IGNORED] /tmp/cloud_health/ confirmed as the correct path; spec reference was outdated.

⚠️ Bug — No credential validation step before push. The code goes straight to "connect & SFTP push" — if SSH auth fails, the user only sees a generic exception. There's no pre-flight validation of inventory credentials.
[PENDING] No pre-flight SSH auth check before SFTP push; SSH failure still surfaces as a generic exception.

⚠️ Bug — _wait_for_port race condition. After nohup ... & is sent via exec_command, the code waits 20s for the local forwarded port to accept connections. If the backend on the bastion crashes immediately (missing Python, missing vendor/, etc.), the user only gets TimeoutError with no diagnostic from backend.log.
[PARTIALLY FIXED] SSH cleanup command added on timeout (pkill + lock removal); backend log is not read back to the frontend on failure.


⚠️ 7. Backend uses SSH connection to stream updates to frontend HTML
Working with caveats.

Backend exposes /ws (WebSocket) on the bastion's localhost ✅
Frontend tunnels through SSH (direct-tcpip channel) and proxies WS messages through WSProxy.proxy_cluster() ✅
Per-check streaming via Section._push() → per-connection asyncio.Queue ✅

⚠️ Subtle bug: In result.py::_push(), queue is put_nowait and silently drops on QueueFull. With maxsize=2000, a slow browser or slow tunnel could lose check results — they will not appear in the frontend, but the backend thinks they were sent. No retry or buffering.
[FIXED] _push() rewritten with backpressure: fast path put_nowait, slow path run_coroutine_threadsafe(queue.put(msg), loop).result(timeout=30).

⚠️ The "SSH connection" claim is misleading per your spec: The actual data path is Browser → Frontend WS → Tunnel (SSH direct-tcpip) → Backend WS. Updates don't stream over a raw SSH channel — they go through a full WebSocket inside the SSH tunnel. Functionally fine, just clarifying.
[IGNORED] Architecture is intentional and functionally correct.


❌ 8. Lock file deleted, SSH closed, frontend updated with failed test details after completion
Partially working — race conditions.

Lock file: _release_lock() is called via atexit, lifespan, and SIGTERM/SIGINT ✅
SSH closed: frontend/app.py finally-block calls await tunnel_mgr.close(ssh) ✅
Frontend updates with failures: reporter_html.py does generate a report, and index.html filter-by-failures works ✅

⚠️ Bug — Lock not released if backend never starts: If _wait_for_port times out, nohup may have spawned the backend on the bastion with the lock acquired. The frontend gives up, closes the tunnel, and the backend on the bastion holds /tmp/cloud_health/hc.lock forever (until the heartbeat watchdog kicks in 60s later — but that only fires after the first activity, not from process start).
[FIXED] SSH cleanup on timeout: pkill -f '/tmp/cloud_health/main.py' and rm -f /tmp/cloud_health/hc.lock sent before raising.

⚠️ Bug in _release_lock(): It tests payload.get("pid") == os.getpid(). The lock file holds pid as an integer (from os.getpid()), but the code branch that handles isinstance(owner_pid, str) only does the str→int coercion in _acquire_lock(), not in _release_lock(). Edge case if the file was written by a different process version — release silently does nothing.
[FIXED] _release_lock() now coerces owner_pid from str to int before comparing to os.getpid().

⚠️ Bug — Heartbeat starts at process start time: _LAST_ACTIVITY = time.monotonic() is set at module import. If a check run takes >60s with no WebSocket message before the first headline, the watchdog will kill the backend mid-run. The heartbeat is reset on each activity after messages flow, but there's a window during cluster connect/SFTP push where it could trigger.
[FIXED] _broadcast() resets _LAST_ACTIVITY = time.monotonic() at the top on every outbound message, eliminating the startup window.


